<subSubSection id="4007B75B391199BF3B7B1F39859E4963" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="10A05C7EDAD8AFB8808F4B95FC67952D" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">
<emphasis id="487D8D72D919062ABE6B225AB375F5F4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Etymology.</emphasis>
-
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CA07C65EDFAC19996C5A86148BBBF668" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">
The species epithet 
<taxonomicName id="FD64258FF87B3A22251EF665E06D5938" authorityName="Um Nyobe, Kekeunou &amp; Bilong Bilong" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" genus="Turanogryllus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Turanogryllus zamakoensis" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zamakoensis">
<emphasis id="7BAE7E41747B1524FC22462678AD2F09" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Turanogryllus zamakoensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
refers to the type locality.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="27964F8D960B766A230F5499FD1E45F0" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="C0EE38D1A662901557D94AF3A94D6C27" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">
<emphasis id="698BF694ECAEC553F167FA34BA4E4860" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
-
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2BDDA25ADDBB3315EBF0BED8C6E61A03" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">
<taxonomicName id="69229567CDE4F3AE5237AE3749B3D119" authorityName="Um Nyobe, Kekeunou &amp; Bilong Bilong" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" genus="Turanogryllus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Turanogryllus zamakoensis" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zamakoensis">
<emphasis id="FE3F49E380777F6B072A2FB695198E16" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Turanogryllus zamakoensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. is distinguished from congeners by light brown coloration, male genitalia provided with a large dorsal lobe of ectoparamere, and with microptereous FWs; the other species are either brachyptereous or macroptereous. In addition, it has only one outer tympanum while the other species have tympana on external and internal side.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="83F13B4B3C866C05BB6E64BC255E6448" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" type="description">
<paragraph id="0597CE016CF321044992DF2C53961EFB" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">
<emphasis id="46496CD55AA477B02D37B73DD7A0875A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Description.</emphasis>
-
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A3E74A105B90106BF826F47B5F11EE8D" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">
(Figs 
<figureCitation id="F43B5A282418415C1A003F1186F54383" captionStart="Fig. 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Fig. 2. Morphology of Turanogryllus zamakoensis sp. nov. A. Male head and pronotum; B. Male lateral view of head and pronotum; C. Male face; D. Female head, pronotum, and FWs; E. Male FW. Scale bars: 10 mm (A); 8 mm (B, C); 7 mm (D); 5 mm (E). Abbreviations: cubital vein, cu. v.; anal vein, a. v. (postcubital vein, Pcu); median vein, m. v.; radial vein, r. v.; subcostal vein and its branches, sc. v.; oblique vein, o. v.; diagonal vein, d. v.; anal node, a. n.; mirror, m.; harp, h.; cord, c.; anal field, a. f.; apical field, ap. f.; lateral field, l. f." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.31.73389.fig2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/690967" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="0A4B2E0C586383AA037EFD2655284C2B" captionStart="Fig. 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Fig. 3. Male genitalia of Turanogryllus zamakoensis sp. nov. A. Dorsal view; B. Ventral view; C. Drawing. Scale bar: 500 µm. Abbreviations: posterior emargination of epiphallus, p. e. e.; stylus, sty.; lateral lobe of epiphallus, l. l. e.; dorsal lobe of ectoparamere, d. l. ect.; ventral lobe of ectoparamere, v. l. ect." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.31.73389.fig3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/690968" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">3</figureCitation>
) 
<emphasis id="0343C73F5C9AFABB9D928825D16F44CD" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Male.</emphasis>
Size average, brown, lighter than other species. Head dark brown with four pale stripes on occiput, not extending over vertex (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="C3D6B422367DB641D300FD98EF69906E" captionStart="Fig. 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Fig. 2. Morphology of Turanogryllus zamakoensis sp. nov. A. Male head and pronotum; B. Male lateral view of head and pronotum; C. Male face; D. Female head, pronotum, and FWs; E. Male FW. Scale bars: 10 mm (A); 8 mm (B, C); 7 mm (D); 5 mm (E). Abbreviations: cubital vein, cu. v.; anal vein, a. v. (postcubital vein, Pcu); median vein, m. v.; radial vein, r. v.; subcostal vein and its branches, sc. v.; oblique vein, o. v.; diagonal vein, d. v.; anal node, a. n.; mirror, m.; harp, h.; cord, c.; anal field, a. f.; apical field, ap. f.; lateral field, l. f." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.31.73389.fig2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/690967" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">2A</figureCitation>
); cheeks pale (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="74675F285A2FE61964504F5735D2DF52" captionStart="Fig. 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Fig. 2. Morphology of Turanogryllus zamakoensis sp. nov. A. Male head and pronotum; B. Male lateral view of head and pronotum; C. Male face; D. Female head, pronotum, and FWs; E. Male FW. Scale bars: 10 mm (A); 8 mm (B, C); 7 mm (D); 5 mm (E). Abbreviations: cubital vein, cu. v.; anal vein, a. v. (postcubital vein, Pcu); median vein, m. v.; radial vein, r. v.; subcostal vein and its branches, sc. v.; oblique vein, o. v.; diagonal vein, d. v.; anal node, a. n.; mirror, m.; harp, h.; cord, c.; anal field, a. f.; apical field, ap. f.; lateral field, l. f." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.31.73389.fig2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/690967" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">2B</figureCitation>
); ocelli large; face entirely pale below median ocellus and below level of antennae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="97625FE3EB3B55359F251F1CF2BAF316" captionStart="Fig. 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Fig. 2. Morphology of Turanogryllus zamakoensis sp. nov. A. Male head and pronotum; B. Male lateral view of head and pronotum; C. Male face; D. Female head, pronotum, and FWs; E. Male FW. Scale bars: 10 mm (A); 8 mm (B, C); 7 mm (D); 5 mm (E). Abbreviations: cubital vein, cu. v.; anal vein, a. v. (postcubital vein, Pcu); median vein, m. v.; radial vein, r. v.; subcostal vein and its branches, sc. v.; oblique vein, o. v.; diagonal vein, d. v.; anal node, a. n.; mirror, m.; harp, h.; cord, c.; anal field, a. f.; apical field, ap. f.; lateral field, l. f." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.31.73389.fig2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/690967" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">2C</figureCitation>
). Pronotum covered with very fine pubescence, without bristles; dorsum dark brown, muscle attachment plates pale brown (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="8A90C9215217271EDB62A1E1579CF1E8" captionStart="Fig. 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Fig. 2. Morphology of Turanogryllus zamakoensis sp. nov. A. Male head and pronotum; B. Male lateral view of head and pronotum; C. Male face; D. Female head, pronotum, and FWs; E. Male FW. Scale bars: 10 mm (A); 8 mm (B, C); 7 mm (D); 5 mm (E). Abbreviations: cubital vein, cu. v.; anal vein, a. v. (postcubital vein, Pcu); median vein, m. v.; radial vein, r. v.; subcostal vein and its branches, sc. v.; oblique vein, o. v.; diagonal vein, d. v.; anal node, a. n.; mirror, m.; harp, h.; cord, c.; anal field, a. f.; apical field, ap. f.; lateral field, l. f." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.31.73389.fig2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/690967" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">2A</figureCitation>
); lateral lobes ivory, becoming dark brown at upper margin (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E14FE37F05B901C4D1AD3F7F8B7E0CD2" captionStart="Fig. 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Fig. 2. Morphology of Turanogryllus zamakoensis sp. nov. A. Male head and pronotum; B. Male lateral view of head and pronotum; C. Male face; D. Female head, pronotum, and FWs; E. Male FW. Scale bars: 10 mm (A); 8 mm (B, C); 7 mm (D); 5 mm (E). Abbreviations: cubital vein, cu. v.; anal vein, a. v. (postcubital vein, Pcu); median vein, m. v.; radial vein, r. v.; subcostal vein and its branches, sc. v.; oblique vein, o. v.; diagonal vein, d. v.; anal node, a. n.; mirror, m.; harp, h.; cord, c.; anal field, a. f.; apical field, ap. f.; lateral field, l. f." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.31.73389.fig2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/690967" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">2B</figureCitation>
). TI and TII ivory-colored; TI with a large outer tympanum. Hindlegs: f FIII pale brown with faintly darker oblique stripes on outer surface; darker around knees, especially on inner surface; TIII pale brown with 6 inner and 7 outer subapical spurs. FWs with square base, reaching abdomen mid-length; its length to pronotal length ratio ca. 2.5; dorsum brown; lateral field pale, dark brown between upper three veins. Stridulatory file with 156 teeth; harp with 3 oblique veins; mirror oval, with one dividing vein (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="0AF880370FFE83AFF82DE37E9C851737" captionStart="Fig. 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Fig. 2. Morphology of Turanogryllus zamakoensis sp. nov. A. Male head and pronotum; B. Male lateral view of head and pronotum; C. Male face; D. Female head, pronotum, and FWs; E. Male FW. Scale bars: 10 mm (A); 8 mm (B, C); 7 mm (D); 5 mm (E). Abbreviations: cubital vein, cu. v.; anal vein, a. v. (postcubital vein, Pcu); median vein, m. v.; radial vein, r. v.; subcostal vein and its branches, sc. v.; oblique vein, o. v.; diagonal vein, d. v.; anal node, a. n.; mirror, m.; harp, h.; cord, c.; anal field, a. f.; apical field, ap. f.; lateral field, l. f." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.31.73389.fig2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/690967" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">2E</figureCitation>
). Hind wings short, hidden by FWs. Abdomen dorsum dark brown; venter pale; cerci pale. Male genitalia (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="25DE140722F624BA13A1FC043DAB8FE0" captionStart="Fig. 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Fig. 3. Male genitalia of Turanogryllus zamakoensis sp. nov. A. Dorsal view; B. Ventral view; C. Drawing. Scale bar: 500 µm. Abbreviations: posterior emargination of epiphallus, p. e. e.; stylus, sty.; lateral lobe of epiphallus, l. l. e.; dorsal lobe of ectoparamere, d. l. ect.; ventral lobe of ectoparamere, v. l. ect." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.31.73389.fig3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/690968" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">3</figureCitation>
): lateral lobes of epiphallus with styli at their posterior extremities, and these styli are provided with bristles; dorsal lobes of ectoparameres lamelliform, curved dorsally in its posterior half; ventral lobes of ectoparameres digitiform, sigmoidally curved; dorsal lobes of ectoparameres enlarged above ventral lobes of ectoparameres.
</paragraph>
